427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.146d4d1f-7959-458c-bb02-b154fe41075c.prompt=PasswordPrompt\: 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.1b9d413d-d2f8-4a07-bac7-3e2ff15f8f7f.prompt=PrivateKeyFile\: 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.1d47222d-ce77-4ebb-9a8f-58dfe2af9fae.prompt=UsernamePrompt\: 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.1f770380-12d0-4533-86e5-addac1cd0cd4.description=
Adds a flow variable into the local context (available to itself and child flows only)

Input Parameters\:
keyName - the name of the flow variable to use
myValue - the value to assign the flow variable

Responses\:
success - assigned the flow variable

Scriptlet Example\:
[$scriptletContext putGlobal\: $keyName, $myValue];
427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.2d105326-1749-4ba1-8804-120d716debe8.prompt=Protocol\: 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.3242c3df-9a0a-48d5-80fc-cad5ba27e41d.prompt=Port\: 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.660dcb1c-2909-4a5a-aeca-01b6c266169e.prompt=Timeout\: 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.aea84ee7-2aac-4a48-957c-86e0b969941e.prompt=SasHostUsername\: 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.c7b02eac-15a7-4a03-867b-86d613329eaa.description=
Runs a command and allows user to specify that it runs locally (in this case no port should be specified), via ssh, Global Shell, ROSH, Telnet, or RSH.

Inputs\:
host - hostname or ip address
port - port number for connecting to the host
username - username to connect as
password - password
protocol - the protocol used to run the command (can be one of ssh, ROSH, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, local, or NASConnectTelnet)
timeout - (optional, default 90 seconds) time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete
command - the command to execute
arguments - the arguments to pass to the command
environment - specifies environment variables/values that need to be defined when running command
startDir - the path to the starting directory
pty - (true, false) whether to use pty
privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.
sasHost - the host we want to run the ROSH command on
sasHostUsername - the username used to run the ROSH command on sasHost
usernamePrompt - the prompt that when seen should send the username; used by the Telnet protocol; when used by the NASConnectTelnet protocol, the default value is 'NAS Login\:'
passwordPrompt - the prompt that when given should send the password; used by the Telnet protocol; when used by the NASConnectTelnet protocol, the default value is 'Password\:'
outputPath - network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified it points to \\host\admin$\temp\'. If this     path is not accessible you should change it to use another share that the host local system account has write access to. By default, the path will have to be  changed on Windows 2000 systems
nasDevice - The NAS device to run the command on when using the NAS connect API protocol.

Responses\:
success - the command was executed successfully
failure - the command could not be executed

Extra Results\:
stdErr - the STDERR of the command
stdOut - the STDOUT of the command
427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.c7c52036-4c07-4192-89d3-1497443ec98c.prompt=OutputPath\: 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.d6a52ade-f525-4c99-a4c2-74ad059d81a7.description=Compares two dates. The inputs must be in the format of date/time format of OO Central Server's, which is dependant of Java Locale. You can use flow " Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format. For exmaple, If OO Central Server's locale is English, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". Inputs\: d1 - The first date. For example, if the locale is English, the format should be "July 12, 2006 4\:23\:20 PM" d2 - The second date. For example, if the locale is English, the format should be "July 12, 2006 4\:23\:20 PM" threshold -The number of milliseconds around each date that still allows the dates to be considered equal. Responses\: before - if d1 is before d2. equal - if d1 is < d2 + threshold and d1 > d2-threshold. after - if d1 is after d2. failure - Something went wrong. Returns\: the value of d1-d2 in milliseconds. 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.d8617834-0314-46e0-a153-d792f77e55cd.description=
Checks to see if a string matches a specific rule.

Inputs\:
matchType - The type of match to perform.
toMatch - The string to check if matches another string.
matchTo - The string to match against.
ignoreCase - Boolean value for whether or not to ignore case during match.

Responses\:
success - The String matched.
failure - The string did not match, or something went wrong.
427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.d87eed75-4e6b-4ce3-9c02-986ec45add87.prompt=SasHost\: 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.db36458e-94df-475a-9957-9fa2c4f44b23.prompt=Pty\: 427502c3-e98e-4823-8075-73e60d2b0870.description=
This determines how long it has been since a file was modified (in minutes) when compared to the given threshold date

Inputs\:
    host -  The system to check
    username - The user to log into this system as
    password - The password to log in with
    dir - The directory to check (should end with a /)
    file - The filename to check
    threshold - A date/time to compare the file modification date/time to.
    port - Port number for connecting to the host
    protocol - The protocol used to run the command (can be one of ssh, ROSH, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, local)
    timeout - (optional, default 90 seconds) Time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete
    pty - (true, false) Whether to use pty
    privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.
    sasHost - The host we want to run the ROSH command on
    sasHostUsername - The username used to run the ROSH command on sasHost
    usernamePrompt - The prompt that when seen should send the username
    passwordPrompt - The prompt that when given should send the password
    outputPath - Network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified it points to \\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible you should change it to use another share that the host local system account has write access to. By default, the path will have to be  changed on Windows 2000 systems
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. For example,  en or ja.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ignored.

Responses\:
   success - Modified date of the file was obtained and also difference between threshold date and modified date was calculated successfully.
   failure - Possible causes for operation failure \:
	a. Invalid threshold date.
	b. ls -l OS command failed.
	c. The modified date is greater than the threshold.

Result\:
   Last modified date of the file.

Extra Results\:
   Code - Return code of the command ls -l, which is used to get the modified date of the file.
   Error String - STDERR of the command.
   TimeDifference - This output gives difference between modified date of the file and threshold date in minutes.
